1
00:00:05,191 --> 00:00:07,651
Welcome to the course
on plasma physics and applications.

2
00:00:08,193 --> 00:00:10,462
Today we will continue
our discussion on how

3
00:00:10,462 --> 00:00:13,748
we can heat the plasma 
and drive current in it using waves.

4
00:00:15,397 --> 00:00:18,455
After a brief reminder
of the fluid dispersion relation —

5
00:00:19,031 --> 00:00:23,078
that is the condition
that we need to impose

6
00:00:23,078 --> 00:00:25,590
in order for the waves 
to propagate in a plasma —

7
00:00:26,270 --> 00:00:29,548
and a brief reminder of the concept
of wave-particle resonance,

8
00:00:29,548 --> 00:00:31,585
which is the mechanism 
by which we transfer energy

9
00:00:31,585 --> 00:00:33,894
from the wave to the plasma,

10
00:00:33,894 --> 00:00:37,429
we will focus on the electron 
cyclotron resonance heating system.

11
00:00:38,975 --> 00:00:44,332
We will see in some degree of detail
what are the physical mechanisms

12
00:00:44,332 --> 00:00:45,822
that are behind it,

13
00:00:45,822 --> 00:00:48,649
how we can avoid 
the reflection layers

14
00:00:48,649 --> 00:00:51,363
for the wave in the plasma
that we refer to as cutoffs

15
00:00:52,166 --> 00:00:54,747
in order to reach 
the absorption layers in the plasma

16
00:00:54,747 --> 00:00:56,730
that we refer to as resonances.

17
00:00:59,141 --> 00:01:01,931
And how we can use 
the two polarizations that characterize

18
00:01:01,931 --> 00:01:04,820
the perpendicular propagation
of the wave in a plasma

19
00:01:05,404 --> 00:01:09,305
in order to do that —
the ordinary and the extraordinary mode.

20
00:01:10,693 --> 00:01:16,259
We will see how we can build
a source of microwaves

21
00:01:17,059 --> 00:01:20,855
that gives the power 
that we need to heat the plasma

22
00:01:20,855 --> 00:01:24,425
at the frequency we need 
to operate — that is the gyrotron.

23
00:01:25,691 --> 00:01:29,688
Then we will illustrate a couple 
of examples of actual systems

24
00:01:29,688 --> 00:01:32,403
that are based on the ECRH
principle to heat the plasma

25
00:01:32,403 --> 00:01:33,986
and drive current into it.

26
00:01:33,986 --> 00:01:37,317
One that already operates
in an actual tokamak,

27
00:01:37,317 --> 00:01:40,435
is the system on the TCV tokamak
here in Lausanne

28
00:01:41,855 --> 00:01:44,417
and the system that we foresee for ITER.

29
00:01:45,589 --> 00:01:49,104
As a brief reminder,
I'll just highlight the fact

30
00:01:49,104 --> 00:01:53,188
that in magnetized plasmas
we can have the propagation

31
00:01:53,188 --> 00:01:54,340
of many modes.

32
00:01:54,887 --> 00:01:56,896
These modes can be used
to transfer energy,

33
00:01:57,318 --> 00:02:00,334
typically via an antenna
or a launcher into the plasma core.

34
00:02:00,714 --> 00:02:03,407
That's the basic principle
of heating plasma using waves.

35
00:02:04,224 --> 00:02:07,317
But I'd also like to remind you
that the frequency

36
00:02:07,317 --> 00:02:10,180
and/or the wavelength 
of these waves must be chosen

37
00:02:10,180 --> 00:02:13,226
in order to satisfy 
the plasma dispersion relation,

38
00:02:13,226 --> 00:02:16,449
that is, the condition for the wave
to exist and propagate in the plasma.

39
00:02:17,117 --> 00:02:19,642
We also need to choose a scenario —

40
00:02:19,642 --> 00:02:21,688
that is a combination 
of frequency and wavelength —

41
00:02:21,688 --> 00:02:24,508
in order to allow the wave
to deposit its energy

42
00:02:24,508 --> 00:02:26,702
in a layer that corresponds
to a plasma resonance,

43
00:02:26,702 --> 00:02:28,146
typically in the plasma core.

44
00:02:29,060 --> 00:02:32,572
Again, as a reminder, 
I'll just highlight

45
00:02:32,572 --> 00:02:36,131
the fact that we have found
that in a fluid model

46
00:02:37,162 --> 00:02:39,661
there are no cyclotron resonances
for propagation,

47
00:02:39,661 --> 00:02:43,417
other than along 
the magnetic field of the plasma.

48
00:02:44,154 --> 00:02:48,314
This is a dispersion relation
that we found in the fluid model

49
00:02:49,781 --> 00:02:52,860
in the direction perpendicular
to the magnetic field

50
00:02:53,291 --> 00:02:56,652
and we see that the resonances
corresponding to the situation

51
00:02:56,652 --> 00:03:00,557
in which the wave number
goes to infinity for a finite frequency

52
00:03:01,135 --> 00:03:04,114
corresponds to the lower hybrid
and upper hybrid frequencies,

53
00:03:04,114 --> 00:03:08,184
respectively, so no resonance
for the cyclotron frequency.

54
00:03:08,657 --> 00:03:14,191
However, we have already seen
in the last lecture

55
00:03:14,191 --> 00:03:16,812
that in the kinetic model,
that is the model that goes

56
00:03:16,812 --> 00:03:18,807
one step beyond the fluid approach,

57
00:03:18,807 --> 00:03:21,593
considering that the velocities 
of the particles are not all the same,

58
00:03:21,593 --> 00:03:24,075
--so we have distributions
that characterize the plasma--

59
00:03:24,553 --> 00:03:27,887
in this model the wave-particle 
resonances exist and occur

60
00:03:28,976 --> 00:03:32,811
when the frequency seen
by the moving particle,

61
00:03:32,811 --> 00:03:35,662
which is of course the frequency
that we launched in the plasma

62
00:03:35,662 --> 00:03:38,259
Doppler-shifted by the k · v there

63
00:03:38,825 --> 00:03:40,943
corresponds either to zero,

64
00:03:40,943 --> 00:03:44,071
which means the plasma wave moves

65
00:03:44,071 --> 00:03:48,766
with a phase velocity that corresponds
to the velocity of the particle

66
00:03:48,766 --> 00:03:52,142
or to multiples
of the cyclotron frequencies.

67
00:03:52,142 --> 00:03:57,230
So we do have cyclotron resonances
in this more advanced model,

68
00:03:58,082 --> 00:04:01,392
even for waves that do not propagate
along the magnetic field.

69
00:04:02,622 --> 00:04:05,950
So the game here is
to reach these resonances,

70
00:04:05,950 --> 00:04:09,967
avoiding the cutoffs,
which are the reflection points.

71
00:04:11,198 --> 00:04:15,008
Reflection points are characterized
by an index of refraction going to zero

72
00:04:15,008 --> 00:04:16,818
that is typically finite ω

73
00:04:16,818 --> 00:04:20,201
and a wave number going to zero.

74
00:04:21,849 --> 00:04:24,411
Although the resonances
cannot be identified

75
00:04:24,411 --> 00:04:27,448
by the fluid model,
at least in perpendicular propagation

76
00:04:27,448 --> 00:04:30,775
or oblique propagation 
in general, the cutoffs can.

77
00:04:31,423 --> 00:04:34,968
In fact, in this dispersion relation
that we have already seen before,

78
00:04:34,968 --> 00:04:38,780
we can identify already cutoff points

79
00:04:38,780 --> 00:04:42,729
such as ωL and ωR

80
00:04:42,729 --> 00:04:46,581
for the extraordinary mode (XM), the mode 
in which the oscillating electric field

81
00:04:46,581 --> 00:04:50,458
is perpendicular
to the ambient magnetic field,

82
00:04:50,458 --> 00:04:54,447
or the ωp cutoff,
which is the well-known cutoff

83
00:04:54,447 --> 00:04:58,690
for the ordinary mode, which corresponds
to the polarization of the wave (OM)

84
00:04:58,690 --> 00:05:02,491
such that the oscillating electric field
of the wave is actually parallel

85
00:05:02,491 --> 00:05:04,909
to the ambient magnetic field.

86
00:05:06,175 --> 00:05:10,018
So these are general concepts
that apply to different kinds of waves

87
00:05:10,018 --> 00:05:14,497
and we're now focusing on the electron
cyclotron resonance heating scheme.

88
00:05:15,437 --> 00:05:17,868
The idea here is to transfer
power to the electrons

89
00:05:18,440 --> 00:05:21,429
at the cyclotron resonance
or at its harmonics.

90
00:05:22,016 --> 00:05:25,374
If I take the fundamental 
cyclotronic frequency,

91
00:05:26,232 --> 00:05:29,397
so n = 1, if you like,
in the previous expression,

92
00:05:30,207 --> 00:05:32,899
and if I express that 
in terms of gigahertz [GHz],

93
00:05:33,826 --> 00:05:38,759
the value that I have is about 28 times
the magnetic field expressed in tesla.

94
00:05:39,201 --> 00:05:44,296
So for a three-tesla device,
we have something on the order

95
00:05:44,296 --> 00:05:47,628
of 100 GHz of frequency
for the electron cyclotron resonance.

96
00:05:48,931 --> 00:05:51,247
At these high frequencies,
the vacuum wavelengths

97
00:05:51,247 --> 00:05:54,969
are relatively small —
they are in the millimeter range.

98
00:05:54,969 --> 00:05:59,384
That implies that the wave propagates
in a quasi-optical manner,

99
00:06:00,366 --> 00:06:04,176
also that the wave is — reasonably
well described in Fourier formalism

100
00:06:04,176 --> 00:06:07,655
and one can use ray or beam tracing
to the describe the propagation

101
00:06:07,655 --> 00:06:09,380
of it into the plasma.

102
00:06:10,266 --> 00:06:14,716
Because the wave is a well-focused beam

103
00:06:15,602 --> 00:06:18,251
we can have local absorption
and therefore local heating

104
00:06:18,251 --> 00:06:20,212
and even local current drive.

105
00:06:21,835 --> 00:06:24,609
Another important point is
there is no need for an antenna

106
00:06:24,609 --> 00:06:27,860
to be placed inside a plasma,
because of this quasi-optical propagation

107
00:06:27,860 --> 00:06:28,787
of the wave.

108
00:06:29,420 --> 00:06:32,534
We need to have a launcher
and/or mirror to steer the beam

109
00:06:32,534 --> 00:06:34,078
in the direction we'd like to go.

110
00:06:36,021 --> 00:06:40,463
The polarization of the wave
can be determined by different components

111
00:06:40,463 --> 00:06:43,177
and controlled by the orientation
of the waveguides and mirrors.

112
00:06:44,259 --> 00:06:48,230
If we inject the wave with
a parallel wave number that's not zero,

113
00:06:48,230 --> 00:06:52,568
in other words we give it 
a direction with a component

114
00:06:52,568 --> 00:06:54,300
along the magnetic field that's not zero,

115
00:06:54,858 --> 00:06:56,684
we can drive current with the wave.

116
00:06:58,458 --> 00:07:01,359
So now we have to choose 
the frequency and the polarization

117
00:07:02,269 --> 00:07:07,614
that are adequate to guarantee two things—
to guarantee what we call accessibility,

118
00:07:07,614 --> 00:07:12,722
that is, again, to reach the resonance
avoiding the cutoff,

119
00:07:12,722 --> 00:07:16,919
which normally is implied by the presence
of a density that's too high.

120
00:07:17,709 --> 00:07:20,545
I notice that in fact, there is
no minimum density requirement

121
00:07:20,545 --> 00:07:23,789
for this scheme, as opposed
to ICRH and lower hybrid

122
00:07:24,306 --> 00:07:28,739
and also, in order to have
a good power absorption in a plasma.

123
00:07:29,143 --> 00:07:32,337
The first scheme we can think of is
the so-called ordinary mode.

124
00:07:32,337 --> 00:07:35,553
As I said before, this is a mode
in which the wave electric field

125
00:07:35,553 --> 00:07:38,874
is parallel to the ambient magnetic field.

126
00:07:38,889 --> 00:07:42,668
Let's illustrate the scenario
that we can operate with.

127
00:07:42,668 --> 00:07:45,411
This is my tokamak plasma cross-section.

128
00:07:46,045 --> 00:07:50,694
I'm coming for practical reasons
from the low field side,

129
00:07:50,694 --> 00:07:54,227
that is, from the outside part
of the tokamak

130
00:07:55,093 --> 00:07:59,440
and I inject my wave
in the radial direction,

131
00:07:59,440 --> 00:08:03,200
perpendicular to B₀,
to the ambient magnetic field.

132
00:08:03,620 --> 00:08:05,806
Now this is the ordinary mode,

133
00:08:06,436 --> 00:08:09,151
so if I take a reference frame here,

134
00:08:09,151 --> 00:08:14,169
I would have a propagation
that would be in the radial direction,

135
00:08:15,331 --> 00:08:19,858
a wave electric field
that would be aligned

136
00:08:19,858 --> 00:08:23,668
with the magnetic field —
of course the wave electric field

137
00:08:23,668 --> 00:08:26,238
will oscillate up and down its sign,

138
00:08:26,238 --> 00:08:29,067
and from the plasma point of view,
we need to consider

139
00:08:29,067 --> 00:08:32,219
where are the cutoffs
and where is the resonance.

140
00:08:35,179 --> 00:08:40,015
Suppose I choose a frequency
for my wave that corresponds

141
00:08:41,245 --> 00:08:44,542
to the cyclotron frequency
at the center of the plasma,

142
00:08:44,542 --> 00:08:46,201
or roughly at the center of the plasma.

143
00:08:46,790 --> 00:08:49,508
I'd like to reach that resonance,

144
00:08:49,508 --> 00:08:52,364
but what do I have to make sure of?

145
00:08:52,983 --> 00:08:55,874
I have to make sure that I don't hit
a cutoff before that.

146
00:08:55,874 --> 00:09:00,747
The cutoff for the ordinary mode
is the plasma frequency [ωp] cutoff,

147
00:09:01,313 --> 00:09:05,342
so there will be a region
that will be inaccessible to my wave

148
00:09:05,342 --> 00:09:09,509
because the frequency will correspond

149
00:09:10,711 --> 00:09:13,888
to a density that will be larger
than the cutoff density.

150
00:09:13,888 --> 00:09:17,059
I'm illustrating that
in a profile of the density itself.

151
00:09:18,159 --> 00:09:20,964
The black region above the cutoff density

152
00:09:20,965 --> 00:09:22,240
is inaccessible.

153
00:09:23,080 --> 00:09:25,461
So in the example here,
I have my wave coming

154
00:09:26,058 --> 00:09:28,238
and before it reaches the resonance,

155
00:09:28,238 --> 00:09:31,796
which is corresponding
to the wave frequency

156
00:09:31,796 --> 00:09:34,514
being equal to the local 
cyclotron frequency—

157
00:09:34,514 --> 00:09:36,592
and I was hoping 
that that would be in the center—

158
00:09:36,592 --> 00:09:40,816
I hit the cutoff relative to the ωp,
to the plasma frequency

159
00:09:40,816 --> 00:09:43,872
which you have seen 
in the previous part of the course.

160
00:09:44,734 --> 00:09:48,973
So I can't have access
to this resonance I was trying to reach.

161
00:09:49,834 --> 00:09:53,746
The only way I can go about that
is to reduce the density

162
00:09:53,746 --> 00:09:58,033
in order to reach the resonant frequency

163
00:09:58,033 --> 00:10:01,533
corresponding to fc before I reach
the corresponding cutoff.

164
00:10:01,533 --> 00:10:04,766
So say I take a lower density.

165
00:10:04,766 --> 00:10:07,940
Then I can indeed heat the plasma

166
00:10:08,755 --> 00:10:14,064
by heating the resonance
before I reach the cutoff,

167
00:10:14,064 --> 00:10:16,083
which corresponds to a reflection point.

168
00:10:16,083 --> 00:10:21,422
So O-mode heating is possible
but only up to a certain density value.

169
00:10:22,240 --> 00:10:25,641
Let us now explore a second option
that we have for the polarization,

170
00:10:25,641 --> 00:10:28,812
the so-called extraordinary 
mode or X-mode

171
00:10:28,820 --> 00:10:35,309
in which the oscillating field of the wave
is perpendicular to the magnetic field.

172
00:10:35,309 --> 00:10:39,153
As we have seen, the dispersion relation
for this mode is quite different

173
00:10:39,153 --> 00:10:40,902
from the ordinary mode.

174
00:10:41,820 --> 00:10:44,426
Let's consider first the first harmonic,

175
00:10:44,426 --> 00:10:47,445
that is, we have 
the frequency of the wave,

176
00:10:47,967 --> 00:10:51,695
roughly chosen to be corresponding
to the resonance frequency

177
00:10:51,695 --> 00:10:56,132
of the electron cyclotron motion
at, say, the plasma core.

178
00:10:58,327 --> 00:11:03,456
I draw my tokamak, 
I inject as before from the low field side

179
00:11:03,456 --> 00:11:07,028
with a waveguide that launches
the waves towards the core.

180
00:11:07,729 --> 00:11:10,239
Polarization now is different.

181
00:11:10,239 --> 00:11:13,789
We have the wave electric field
that's perpendicular

182
00:11:13,789 --> 00:11:16,533
to the ambient magnetic field,

183
00:11:16,905 --> 00:11:19,894
and the wave vector that is
perpendicular to both

184
00:11:19,894 --> 00:11:21,722
and is directed
in the radial direction.

185
00:11:21,722 --> 00:11:26,360
So we have, say, the cyclotron frequency

186
00:11:26,880 --> 00:11:28,333
roughly in the center.

187
00:11:28,333 --> 00:11:30,002
That's the fc resonance.

188
00:11:31,026 --> 00:11:33,228
But for the extraordinary mode,

189
00:11:34,460 --> 00:11:36,624
we also have the upper hybrid resonance,

190
00:11:38,136 --> 00:11:43,079
whose shape is dictated
by the combination of the magnetic field

191
00:11:43,079 --> 00:11:44,880
and of the plasma density.

192
00:11:44,880 --> 00:11:48,184
And we have the x-mode cutoff,

193
00:11:48,891 --> 00:11:52,494
which is well represented by 
the fluid, the special relation,

194
00:11:52,494 --> 00:11:56,653
which is to the right-hand side
of the upper hybrid resonance.

195
00:11:56,653 --> 00:12:00,313
So this is my resonance,
upper hybrid resonance,

196
00:12:00,313 --> 00:12:02,096
and this is the cutoff layer.

197
00:12:02,096 --> 00:12:07,677
So in fact, that means
there's a forbidden area

198
00:12:07,677 --> 00:12:10,175
for propagation between the two.

199
00:12:11,579 --> 00:12:14,235
And if the wave comes
from the low field side,

200
00:12:14,235 --> 00:12:17,942
it's bound to meet first the cutoff layer

201
00:12:17,942 --> 00:12:22,010
before it can have a chance
of meeting the upper hybrid

202
00:12:22,010 --> 00:12:24,633
or the electron cyclotron resonance.

203
00:12:24,633 --> 00:12:26,598
So this cannot work

204
00:12:27,046 --> 00:12:30,048
because the wave 
cannot reach any resonance.

205
00:12:30,640 --> 00:12:32,997
So what can we do
to improve the situation?

206
00:12:33,933 --> 00:12:38,136
The idea is to go to higher harmonics —

207
00:12:39,207 --> 00:12:44,560
say the second or even third harmonic
of the electron cyclotron frequency.

208
00:12:45,552 --> 00:12:47,781
Let's take the example
of the second harmonic.

209
00:12:48,738 --> 00:12:53,020
The frequency of the wave
will be chosen to correspond roughly

210
00:12:53,020 --> 00:12:56,696
to two times the electron 
cyclotron frequency

211
00:12:56,696 --> 00:12:59,390
in the plasma core
or close to the center.

212
00:13:01,993 --> 00:13:07,941
I'm still coming from the low field side
with my wave, exact same way as before.

213
00:13:13,698 --> 00:13:17,346
Electric field perpendicular to B₀
and with a wave vector

214
00:13:17,346 --> 00:13:18,627
that's directed radially.

215
00:13:18,627 --> 00:13:21,017
Why does this help me?

216
00:13:21,970 --> 00:13:23,797
What have I done to improve the situation?

217
00:13:23,797 --> 00:13:29,120
Well, I have essentially taken
the first harmonic resonance

218
00:13:29,120 --> 00:13:34,709
and the upper hybrid resonance
and the cutoff all the way to the left.

219
00:13:34,709 --> 00:13:38,503
I have moved them all the way to the left

220
00:13:38,503 --> 00:13:43,774
so that they can be —
the fc can even be outside a plasma —

221
00:13:43,774 --> 00:13:46,156
it doesn't really matter anymore.

222
00:13:46,663 --> 00:13:49,994
Upper hybrid would be
somewhere in the plasma, of course —

223
00:13:49,994 --> 00:13:55,131
this is my upper hybrid layer —
this is the X-mode cutoff.

224
00:13:55,723 --> 00:14:01,561
And the point is that the resonance
that I'm trying to reach,

225
00:14:01,561 --> 00:14:05,221
which is the 2fce resonance,

226
00:14:05,793 --> 00:14:08,583
is now in front of the cutoff layer.

227
00:14:09,043 --> 00:14:13,088
So my wave coming from the right
can indeed hit that resonance

228
00:14:13,088 --> 00:14:17,686
before it hits any cutoff layer,
so before it's reflected back

229
00:14:17,686 --> 00:14:20,830
from the plasma
back to the antenna on the launcher.

230
00:14:22,147 --> 00:14:24,801
So this is a situation
which we can envisage

231
00:14:24,801 --> 00:14:26,891
to heat the plasma

232
00:14:27,792 --> 00:14:31,489
and even, if we direct
the wave in a particular direction,

233
00:14:31,491 --> 00:14:33,585
drive current non-inductively through it.

234
00:14:33,953 --> 00:14:36,751
Now we note we can't really 
continue the scheme —

235
00:14:36,751 --> 00:14:41,132
we can think of having 
the third harmonic also,

236
00:14:41,132 --> 00:14:48,668
and therefore increase the density value
corresponding to the X-mode cutoff

237
00:14:49,495 --> 00:14:52,546
but we can't do that indefinitely
because we have, first of all,

238
00:14:52,546 --> 00:14:57,702
a reduced absorption efficiency
as we go to higher and higher harmonics.

